      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Horsemouth wrote:</div><div class="orig">As the new class changes are upon us what do you folks think will end up being different in that magical, awkward and bizarre time that is the post Wrath pre Cata period of time? </div></div> <br /> <br /><span class="sm"><i>That's great, it starts with an earthquake, birds and snakes, an aeroplane - someproteinguy is not afraid.</i></span> <br /> <br />I'm kind of glad they're giving us two months to sort things out. I think some people will need it. Not that we're all terrible or anything, I think there are just a lot of bad habits that people have gotten into these last few months that will take some unlearning. <br /> <br />Example: <br /> <br />I was DPSing the other day in Nexus on my Warlock. As a bit of background, I've missed out on DPSing all of Wrath pretty much, as I've been tanking/healing. This was my first 5-man instance on the warlock, and the last time I DPSed with any consistency was way way back in BC with my hunter. Anyway I'm in Nexus with a friend who has spent Wrath on his hunter (he's on a druid alt), and a warrior tank who, is just starting to learn the ropes. <br /> <br />Anyway we're working though the instance, and he's pulling aggro left and right. Mostly by hitting AoE too soon, <span class="sm"><i>Eye of a hurricane, listen to yourself churn, world serves its own needs, dummy serve your own needs.</i></span> and peeling mobs off the tank, not being careful with his positioning and what not. Now I know the guy is a good player and all, he's our top DPS in raids, and is generally pretty far up there on the competence scale. It's just this tank doesn't have the snap aggro that a more experienced/geared tank would have, <span class="sm"><i>Look at that low playing! Fine, then.</i></span> and I don't think he was used to it. <br /> <br />Now a new tank is fine, and I'm not going to go hard on someone learning the ropes. So I scaled back my own crazy AoEness, but my friend kept right on going. By the end of the dungeon, I think he had died 4-5 times, and the healer was getting pretty upset with him. <span class="sm"><i>Offer me solutions, offer me alternatives and I decline.</i></span> Pulling aggro that much, doesn't make you popular. In this time I had managed to pull aggro once, and dropped quickly with soulshatter. So what did my friend get out of it? Well his DPS was about 300 points higher (1500 vs 1200 in normal nexus in the low 70s), and probably would have been even higher if he didn't spend half the instance splatted on the floor. <br /> <br />Now this is probably partly poor playing on my part at the moment. I'm still not really used to AoE, and I still get nervous when I have to launch it. <span class="sm"><i>Uh-oh, this means no fear cavalier. Renegade steer clear!</i></span> Honestly I'm used to the hunter, and having a 5min CD on volley still... <img border="0" src="http://common.zam.com/shared/smilies/lol.gif" alt="Smiley: lol"/> I'm starting to think this will work to my benefit though, and there will be a little less unlearning to do here shortly.  <br /> <br />As for my friend? I'm sure he'll be fine. Bad habits do take time to break, but he'll get over it. People will play to the level of challenge they are presented with. Better players that have been slacking will rise to the occasion and such. <span class="sm"><i>and I feel fine.</i></span> There will be a couple of weeks of crazy I'm sure, there's a lot changing. But people will figure it out in the end. <br /> <br />Anyway I'm going to stop now. I'm rambling and apparently have a song stuck in my head... <img border="0" src="http://common.zam.com/shared/smilies/rolleyes.gif" alt="Smiley: rolleyes"/><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>NO. You will NOT break the $%#&amp; shackle! <br /> <br />Know a blog you'd like to see highlighted? <a href="HTTP://wow.allakhazam.com/s