      <div class="msgContentFrame">This constant slagging off of DPS is a bit wearing, I have to say.  <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">As DPS my job is to do as much damage as threat allows and help the team kill the bosses. That's it. Easiest job in the game.</div></div> <br /> <br />You're generally supposed to CC and interrupt, too. On a tank and spank mob, all roles are incredibly easy; any rotation is only difficult if it has to be modified, as challenge comes from reacting to change rather than repeating a simple sequence. CC (less so) and interrupts are always reactive.  <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">As a tank my job is keep the healer alive. DPS dying to fire or threat are on their own. It's not like tanks have a button that's ZOMG THREAT BEAST that we're not using &quot;just in case&quot;. Tanks have a set of standard abilities that produce a relatively steady stream of threat. Aside from taunts, a competent tank will output a basic mean-average of threat per second. Hitting buttons harder don't give additional threat, sadly.</div></div> <br /> <br />Uh, yeah, but there are plenty of ways to stop people dying when they over aggro - any of many taunts, charge, BoP, feral charge, HoS, bash, shockwave, intervene chains etc etc, and you can certainly use them to do so. If all you're doing is running up to a group and completing a threat rotation then I struggle to see how that's harder than running up and dropping a DPS rotation. And hey, if the dps is doing anythign else (and they should be!) that sort of makes your job even easier than theirs, doesn't it? <br /> <br />Is it your job to save them, though? Well, who knows. Is it my job to resheep my focus when some idiot hits bladeflurry standing right by it? Is it my job to nova the mobs that came for the priest 'cause the tank couldn't hold multi-target aggro? Your whole &quot;not my job&quot; spiel seems rather in conflict with the whole teamwork thing you're going for. Sure, if you don't think you can help a DPS without everyone else dying - and the mob will come back to you after, rather than snacking on the second dps and wiping you anyway - sure, you have to let him die. Otherwise? Ask them to be more careful, to play better, and try and keep the group alive and with as few repairs as possible. If it's really that big a problem then kick them and get someone else. <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">99% of groups were fine with it, tanks are held in higher esteem than other roles from what I've noticed. Again, this is from playing DPS and Tanking all the way from regular 5 mans through ICC. Most players don't understand tanking, and to be honest, it scares them, it scared the hell out of me for oh I dunno, about 8 years now?</div></div>  <br /> <br />Having tried both (mage, rogue, prot/ret paladin, feral druid) I don't really think tanking is harder than DPSing, and if people hold it in awe (I suspect they just don't want to piss tanks off as they're rarer) it's probably out of ignorance. I dunno, I think you're projecting, but it's perfectly possible that it's me that's incorrect in assuming most people feel the way I do about it; I've never felt intimidated by tanking. <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">I love my tank, to be honest, I like playing him more than my DPS classes, but no matter how much fun I'm having, it's still stressful.</div></div>  <br /> <br />I can understand this, at least. There are generally three DPS in a group, and so certain failures (interrupting, CC, not enough boss dps) can be more easily compensated for by better play by others, especially if you slightly out-gear the instance, though the first two may well wipe the group a few times before you get put in the kiddy-pool. As the MT in a raid, while your job isn't, generally speaking much harder, your mistakes are likely the costliest for the raid. <br /> <br />All these &quot;generally&quot;s are there because obviously certain encounters are tougher for certain roles/classes.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>How to play the Cameron drinking game: every time David Cameron is elected Prime Minister you drink for five years. <br /> <br />Koalotter buoyed by Kirby.</div></div>
