      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Labiarinth wrote:</div><div class="orig">I have a bunch of toons (almost embarrassed to admit how many 80's). I've done plenty of dpsing, healing, and tanking. Imho, that's the order of difficulty. <br /> <br />Dps is pretty easy. It's harder to do it well, but it's still not that hard. <br /> <br />Healing is usually pretty easy, but it can be tricky sometimes. If the tank is undergeared or you are barely high enough level and tend to run out of mana, or if there is some terrible situation with an unexpected pat or something, well, it can get hairy. Most of the time it's not bad, though. If the group is overgeared (WoLK heroics in the past year or so), you can practically snooze through it. 11121112111... snore... <br /> <br />Tanking isn't always hard. If the healer is good and the dps aren't stupid, it can be pretty smooth. If the dps run amok AOE-ing every group of mobs the escond they see it, or if the healer is kinda ADD, or if someone's pet does something crazy, it can be very difficult. And you always have to know the route to take, and where the pats are, and you have to keep an eye on threat, etc etc. Even an easy run takes a certain amount of effort and attention. <br /> <br />That's just my two scents. <br /></div></div> <br /> <br />I'm somewhat opposite in my feelings on this.  <br /> <br />I find healing the easiest of the 3. Or at least the &quot;least involved&quot; of the 3. I don't need to worry about rotations or watch meters or even know where I'm at or who we're fighting. I watch my x-perl frames and heal whomever is lit up red and cleanse whomever is lit up blue. As an example, with my new guild (who actually raid, yay!) I have now healed the first 5 or 6 bosses of ICC twice. I have no idea what bosses they were or which way we went. I know who was tanking, whom to beacon, and that nobody died. I never SEE any of the actual fights and rarely have any clue what actually went on. <br /> <br />I also find tanking to be somewhat more relaxing than many others seem to. I get to set the pace and make the pulls. All I have to worry about is wrapping up the mobs, positioning them, and waiting til they die. I rarely lose threat unless somebody is actually *trying* to pull. Again, don't need to worry about meters or people's health since I can see I have aggro. It is the polar opposite of healing though in that I know the exact layout of everything, where every mob and patrol is, what all of them do, who to force-pull and who will come to me, etc. <br /> <br />DPS is sort of split for me. On my warlock it's easy. Stand by the healer, have the time to see everything happening, simple rotation, big DPS, and I can easily pull a runner off a healer or other dps if needed. On my melee toons I find it more stressful than tanking honestly. Both my warrior and rogue I seem to have to find *just* the right place to attack from and dance around wherever the tank happens to be dragging them before starting in on a more complicated priority matrix of abilities; I can never seem to see what's going on or anything with me, the tank, the mobs, and any other melee all stacked up in a pile under the flashing damage numbers and DBM warnings. And with all DPS, it is of course a customary and mandatory recount wankfest wherein your only perceived value is how high your leet deeps is.</div>
