      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Overlord Theophany wrote:</div><div class="orig"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Lyrailis wrote:</div><div class="orig">The challenge is, and has always been, Healer &gt; Tank &gt; DPS.</div></div> <br />Tell that to my guild who wiped every damn time on Brutallus because of enrage. <br /> <br />Optimizing your DPS (especially casted DPS, where channeled and casted spells are absolutely essential to optimizing your DPS), staying out of AoE effects, and pushing every single ounce of DPS possible out of your class to beat his enrage timer wasn't exactly a cake-walk. <br /> <br />I know as a rogue on that encounter if you missed one or two GCDs, your DPS dropped by ~10% if not more, meaning if your guild was beating his enrage timer by a second or two, you were basically @#%^ed. <br /> <br />Obviously nothing is really like that in WotLK raiding (<i>maybe</i> hard mode ICC), but while we can all generalize and say that &quot;XXX is the easiest role in the game!&quot;, it doesn't hold true over the whole game. <br /> <br />Edit: our healers were awful, BTW, yet we managed to never get passed Brutallus. We had one good priest, and that was about it. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Oct  6th 2010  4:38pm by Theophany </span></i></div></div> <br /> <br />You managed to point out the 1% of the time where that _isn't_ true. <br /> <br />Okay, I'll amend my earlier statement: <br /> <br />&quot;In Wrath, Pre 4.0, for 90% of PvE grouping content, the challenge level looks like this: Healer &gt; Tank &gt; DPS&quot; <br /> <br />Does that sound better? <br /> <br />Edit: I'll also note that if I recall correctly, I know Blizz said they wanted to make cat druids' rotations a little more forgiving, they know that missing a single GCD can result in massive DPS drops. I think they also said they wanted to do similar to Rogues? <br /> <br />But then for that matter, they are trying to make healing better too. <br /> <br />But as it stands, in Wrath, 90% of the time, DPS is dead last in challenge, with the healers on top as the &quot;OMG, you can't do ANYTHING wrong!&quot; and tanks being somewhere in the middle, depending on which class you're playing. <br /> <br />Edit2: Also, the Gear equivalent: Increasing your gear as a DPS has a direct, easily-seen number representation. A bad DPS who doesn't know his exact rotation, and/or who isn't <i>quite</i> optimized can just grab a few pieces of the next tier when it comes out and increase his DPS by a good margin, even if his technique is still sub-optimal. However, a tank who is letting mobs hit him in the back, a tank that is failing to use things like Shield Block, Holy Shield, etc, a tank who is failing to pop cooldowns when needed is still going to take far more damage than he should, even if he adds a little extra stam and avoidance. And then, the healer, doesn't matter how much +spellpower, +crit, and +haste you stick on, a bad healer who has poor reaction times, doesn't know the fights, yadda yadda is still going to let people die regardless if he's wearing i200 or i251s. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Oct  6th 2010  7:55pm by Lyrailis </span></i> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Oct  6th 2010  7:59pm by Lyrailis </span></i></div>
